{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2a987252-e016-42d1-b93d-62efea7e1646","content":"Here's what I found in `my_app/views.py`:\n\n**Line 3** — `datetime.now()` is called directly, making this hard to test because you can't control or freeze the clock in unit tests.\n\n### Recommendation\n\nInject the dependency instead. Two common Django-friendly fixes:\n\n1. **Use `django.utils.timezone.now`** (preferred in Django) and mock it in tests:\n   ```python\n   from django.utils import timezone\n   def index(request):\n       now = timezone.now()\n       ...\n   ```\n   Then in tests: `@mock.patch('django.utils.timezone.now')`\n\n2. **Inject a clock function** for full control:\n   ```python\n   def index(request, clock=timezone.now):\n       now = clock()\n       ...\n   ```\n\nThis was the only file in the project — just the one static call found. The project is small, so the fix is straightforward.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d0ebfd10-309f-41c3-86fc-3038b1d2c420","outputTokens":223,"requestId":"4C1F:389019:B8EAB9:E26535:6A01445A"},"id":"d1771fe7-ab2c-4584-bc00-cdc4ea5365d0","timestamp":"2026-05-11T02:52:16.772Z","parentId":"692d60b5-1388-4eba-9e9f-9f4e73064ce3"}
